[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Architecture Expert Review
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What's Done Well
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Eight-stage architecture (channel entry, input safety screening, intent classification, identity verification, conversational slot negotiation, transactional fulfillment, output safety screening, audit and log and telemetry) is the right shape for the simple-medium-tier slot and is recipe-distinct from 11.1's seven-stage decomposition.** The two new stages (identity verification, transactional fulfillment) and the new cross-cutting design points (tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, transactional-failure compensation) are correctly elevated.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Tool surface as the bot's contract with the scheduling system is correctly elevated as the central architectural primitive.** "The tools have versioned schemas. The schemas are owned jointly by the engineering team and the practice operations team. Changes to the tool surface (adding a parameter, changing the rank order in slot search, deprecating a tool) go through a documented change-management process. The bot's behavior is reproducible from the conversation log plus the active tool-surface version plus the active prompt and model versions. This is the load-bearing contract that makes the system safe to put in front of patients."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Identity verification graduated by intent and channel is correctly architected.** Step 3 pseudocode with the authenticated-session short-circuit, the unauthenticated-channel collection-and-confirmation flow, the step-up authentication for sensitive actions, the no-match and ambiguous-match handling, the below-threshold handoff, is the architecturally-correct graduated-assurance pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Slot hold as the safety net for concurrency is correctly architected.** "Without slot hold, two patients can race to book the same slot through different channels and one of them ends up double-booked. Slot hold with a TTL is the mechanism that prevents this. The bot's flow is always search-then-hold-then-confirm-then-book, never search-then-book. The TTL is short enough that abandoned holds release quickly (5 minutes is typical) and long enough that a patient deliberating over options has time to choose."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Visit-type mapping as managed asset is correctly architected.** "The mapping from natural-language reasons for visit ('I need to follow up after my stress test') to institutional visit types ('cardiology established patient follow-up, 30 min') is a curated artifact owned by the practice operations team. The bot uses an LLM to do the mapping with the curated visit-type catalog as context, and the operations team reviews mis-mapped cases through the sampled review queue. The mapping evolves as the institution adds, retires, or restructures visit types."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Booking is durable and the conversation is not.** Step 6D pseudocode with the booking-event-journal write to S3 with Object-Lock-in-compliance-mode is the architecturally-correct durable-record pattern; the "the source of truth is the scheduling system. The conversation log is the audit trail of how the booking happened, but the appointment itself lives in the scheduling system" framing earns its position as the recipe's clearest articulation of the durable-record-versus-conversation distinction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Compensation as first-class operation is correctly elevated.** "When the bot books an appointment that turns out to be wrong (wrong visit type, wrong provider, wrong location, wrong time, wrong patient), the operational team needs to be able to undo and redo the booking cleanly. The architecture supports this with explicit 'view this booking's history' and 'compensate this booking' operations in the operational tooling. The audit trail for the original booking and the compensation is preserved together so that the institution can reproduce the full sequence of events for any patient complaint or any audit request."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Output safety screening with booking-claim verification is the recipe-distinct architectural primitive.** Step 9B `extract_booking_claims(response)` with `find_supporting_tool_call(claim, tool_call_history)` is the architecturally-correct hallucination-defense primitive for transactional bots; the "did the bot tell the patient an appointment was booked when the booking tool did not actually return success" framing earns its position.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Bedrock Agents for tool orchestration with custom Lambda orchestrator as alternative is the architecturally-correct managed-offering-with-flexibility-tradeoff substrate.** "Agents is the faster path; the custom orchestrator is more flexible and is sometimes preferred for institutions that need fine-grained control over the orchestration behavior. Both work; the tradeoff is build time versus flexibility."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **No-show and reminder workflows as integrations not features.** "The institution's existing reminder workflow (text reminders, phone-call reminders, email reminders) is a separate system. The booking tool triggers it as part of the standard booking flow. The bot does not own these workflows; the bot's job is to integrate cleanly with them so that the patient's experience is consistent regardless of whether the appointment was booked through the bot, the call center, or the portal."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Channel entry with greeting and disclosure is correctly architected.** Step 1B pseudocode attaches the greeting-and-disclosure on the first message of a new session: "Identifies as a chatbot, not a human... States the bot's scope (scheduling, rescheduling, cancellation; not clinical)... Offers an immediate path to a human."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Refinement loop with re-search on patient modifications is correctly architected.** Step 5 pseudocode with the `apply_refinement(current_parameters, refinement)` and re-search-and-re-offer flow handles the "anything earlier?" / "different day?" / "different provider?" patient-modification pattern naturally; the modern-LLM-handles-multi-turn-coherence framing in the Technology section earns its position.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **No-results handling with explicit alternatives is correctly architected.** Step 4E pseudocode with the wait-list enrollment, alternative provider, alternative location, telehealth alternative, live-scheduler handoff alternatives is the architecturally-correct honest-no-results-handling pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Slot-race recovery with hold-failure handling is correctly architected.** Step 5B `slot_hold_tool.invoke(...)` with the `outcome == "no_longer_available"` re-search-and-re-offer branch is the architecturally-correct recovery pattern; the >99% slot-race-recovery-rate framing in the Performance benchmarks earns its position.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Reschedule and cancel flows with policy step-up checks correctly elevate the institutional-policy-as-bot-configuration discipline.** Step 7 pseudocode with the appointment_lookup, the policy.evaluate, the requires_step_up branch, the routing to execute_cancel or execute_reschedule is the architecturally-correct workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Booking-failure handling with disposition-specific recovery is correctly architected.** Step 8 pseudocode with the slot-no-longer-available, scheduling-system-error, policy-violation, duplicate-booking dispositions and the per-disposition response template is the architecturally-correct partial-failure-handling pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Conversation-close with audit-and-telemetry-and-cohort-metric emission is correctly architected.** Step 10 pseudocode with the audit_record assembly, the EventBridge lifecycle event emission, and the per-cohort BookingCompleted and TimeToBooking metric emission is the architecturally-correct close pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Cost-estimate framing with the per-booking infrastructure cost dominated by Bedrock LLM invocation volume and Knowledge Bases hosting earns its position.** "The per-booking infrastructure cost is small relative to the operational savings versus live-scheduler handling of the same booking" is the recipe's clearest articulation of the build-vs-buy economics primitive.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The Variations and Extensions section's thirteen-extension enumeration is well-scoped** and frames each extension at the right grain.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The Honest Take's seven-trap enumeration covers the recipe's central operational risks** including the recipe-distinct first trap (visit-type-catalog-as-someone-else's-problem with the three-months-of-cleanup-as-pre-deployment-investment framing), second trap (underestimating-the-EHR-integration with the major-EHRs-vary-substantially-in-implementation-completeness framing), fifth trap (identity-verification-as-friction-problem-rather-than-safety-primitive), and sixth trap (slot-hold-and-book-transactional-contract-as-engineering-nicety).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Finding A1: Per-Cohort Booking-Completion and Identity-Verification-Success Monitoring with Launch-Gate Discipline Architecturally Implicit Despite Recipe's Own Elevation as Central Trap, with Recipe-Distinct Per-Language-by-Channel-by-Visit-Type Three-Axis-Cohort and Identity-Verification-Friction-as-Equity-Metric Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Severity:** HIGH
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Expert:** Architecture (per-cohort-validation-as-launch-gate, per-population-disparity-as-equity-monitoring, multi-axis-cohort-stratification, identity-verification-friction-as-equity-metric)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Location:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   - Step 10C `cloudwatch.put_metric` calls with `dimensions: { channel, language, assurance_level, intent }` for BookingCompleted and `dimensions: { channel, language, visit_type }` for TimeToBooking.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   - Cross-Cutting Design Points "Per-cohort monitoring is non-negotiable" paragraph: "Booking completion rates and identity-verification success rates can vary substantially by language, age cohort, channel, and (where available) other equity-relevant axes. The institution monitors these from launch and treats per-cohort disparity as a launch-gate criterion, not a post-launch dashboard."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   - Production-Gaps "Per-cohort accuracy and equity monitoring with launch gates" paragraph: "The booking-completion rate, the identity-verification success rate, the time-to-booking, the patient-feedback distribution all vary by cohort. Per-language, per-channel, per-age-cohort, per-region. Build the monitoring as a launch gate: each cohort must meet the threshold before the cohort goes live. Aggregate metrics hide failures that subgroup metrics surface."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   - Honest Take's seventh trap on quality measurement: "The metric mix includes: booking completion rate, time to booking, identity-verification success rate, mis-booked visit type rate, slot-hold-but-not-confirmed rate, tool-call success rate per tool, handoff rate per intent and per failure mode, patient-feedback distribution, per-cohort metric slices."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   - Where-it-Struggles "Identity-verification friction for elderly or technologically less-comfortable patients" paragraph.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** Same chapter pattern as 11.1 Finding A1, with recipe-distinct extensions. The recipe correctly elevates per-cohort monitoring as a central trap and correctly identifies per-language, per-channel, per-age-cohort, and per-region as cohort axes. The CloudWatch metric dimensions correctly include `channel`, `language`, `assurance_level`, `intent`, and `visit_type`. Despite the correct elevation, the architecture pattern, the diagram, and the cross-cutting design points do not specify:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   1. **Per-cohort launch-gate threshold values.** The Production-Gaps paragraph names the launch-gate discipline but the architecture pattern treats it as a post-launch concern. Per-cohort booking-completion-rate thresholds, per-cohort identity-verification-success-rate thresholds, per-cohort time-to-booking thresholds, per-cohort mis-booked-visit-type-rate ceilings, per-cohort slot-hold-but-not-confirmed-rate ceilings, per-cohort tool-call-failure-rate ceilings, per-cohort handoff-rate ceilings should be defined per cohort with launch gating.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   2. **Per-cohort sample-size minimums for statistical reliability.** Per-cohort accuracy with low per-cohort sample sizes produces noisy metrics that may not surface real disparities; the architecture should specify the per-cohort minimum sample size and the per-cohort sample-aggregation cadence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   3. **Two-axis and three-axis cohort stratification for equity-acute combinations.** A Spanish-speaking patient on a smartphone using web chat for a cardiology follow-up is the equity-stake-population; the per-language single-axis cohort and the per-channel single-axis cohort do not surface the intersection-population's disparity. The architecture should specify per-language-by-channel, per-language-by-intent, per-language-by-visit-type, per-channel-by-visit-type, per-assurance-level-by-channel two-axis stratification at minimum, with per-language-by-channel-by-visit-type three-axis stratification for the multilingual-multi-specialty deployments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   4. **Cohort-disabled-feature workflow.** When a per-cohort metric drifts below the institutional threshold, the architecture should specify the operational response: surface the disabled status to clinicians or patient-experience operators; document the disabled period and the remediation actions for institutional review; potentially route the cohort to live-scheduler handoff during the remediation window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   5. **Sustained-utilization rate as per-cohort metric.** A per-cohort booking-completion rate that meets the threshold but per-cohort sustained-utilization that does not (patients increasingly bypass the bot for the call center; patients increasingly request human handoff mid-conversation) is an institutional-equity-failure even though the technology is technically meeting its bar. The metric should be defined and monitored.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   6. **Identity-verification-friction-as-equity-metric is the recipe-distinct dimension.** Per the recipe's own Where-it-Struggles framing, identity-verification friction disproportionately affects elderly and technologically-less-comfortable patients. Per-cohort identity-verification-success rate is the recipe-distinct equity-acute metric; the architecture should specify per-cohort identity-verification-success rate, per-cohort identity-verification-attempts-before-success, per-cohort identity-verification-handoff-rate (where the bot gives up and routes to a human), and per-cohort identity-verification-abandonment-rate (where the patient gives up).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   7. **Mis-booked-visit-type-rate as per-cohort metric is recipe-distinct.** Per the recipe's central first trap (visit-type-catalog-as-someone-else's-problem), the visit-type mapping is the load-bearing operational quality concern. Per-cohort mis-booked-visit-type-rate (measured via downstream operational signal: did the operations team have to clean up the booking by rescheduling to the right visit-type) is the recipe-distinct equity-acute metric.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   8. **Per-cohort retrieval-versus-generation-versus-tool-orchestration decomposition.** A per-cohort booking-completion failure may be retrieval-side (the visit-type catalog is biased away from the cohort's phrasing), generation-side (the LLM does not synthesize a useful conversation for the cohort's literacy level), or tool-orchestration-side (the agent makes the wrong tool-call decisions for the cohort). The architecture should specify the per-cohort decomposition.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   Recipe-acute amplification because the scheduling bot is the chapter's first transactional bot and the patient-experience improvements the recipe sells are bounded above by the per-cohort equity profile; the institutional habits set here propagate forward into the harder transactional recipes.
